{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inline vs Named Handlers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "React event props accept any function. In practice you will write handlers two ways: as an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "inline arrow function"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " defined directly in JSX, or as a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "named function"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " declared in the component body. Both are valid. Knowing when to use which — and understanding the real trade-offs — leads to code that is easier to read, test, and maintain."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Side-by-side comparison of inline arrow function and named handler — pros and cons of each",
          "title": "Inline vs Named handlers"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inline Arrow Functions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An inline arrow creates the function expression directly inside the JSX attribute."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Inline arrow — the entire handler is written inside the prop\nfunction Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n  return (\n    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n      Count: {count}\n    </button>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every time the component renders, JavaScript creates a new function object for the arrow. The function closes over the current "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "count"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " value from that render, which is usually what you want."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When inline arrows shine"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Trivial single-expression logic"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if the whole handler is one setter call, an inline arrow is the cleaner option. Naming it "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "handleToggleCheckbox"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " for "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "() => setChecked(!checked)"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " adds no information."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Passing arguments from a list"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — when you need to close over an item-specific value (like an "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "id"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "), an inline arrow is the natural fit."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Prototype and throwaway code"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — inline arrows let you iterate quickly without naming every action."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Good uses of inline arrows\nfunction TodoList({ todos, onDelete, onToggle }) {\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {todos.map(todo => (\n        <li key={todo.id}>\n          <input\n            type=\"checkbox\"\n            checked={todo.done}\n            onChange={() => onToggle(todo.id)}      // closes over todo.id\n          />\n          {todo.text}\n          <button onClick={() => onDelete(todo.id)}>  {/* closes over todo.id */}\n            Remove\n          </button>\n        </li>\n      ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Named Functions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A named handler is a regular function declared in the component body and referenced by name in JSX."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function LoginForm() {\n  const [email, setEmail]       = useState('');\n  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');\n  const [error, setError]       = useState(null);\n\n  function handleSubmit(e) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    if (!email.includes('@')) {\n      setError('Enter a valid email');\n      return;\n    }\n    setError(null);\n    submitLogin({ email, password });\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <input value={email}    onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} />\n      <input value={password} onChange={e => setPassword(e.target.value)} type=\"password\" />\n      {error && <p>{error}</p>}\n      <button type=\"submit\">Login</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Notice the form uses "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onSubmit={handleSubmit}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (named, because it has multi-step logic) while the inputs use inline arrows (single-expression setters). This is the pattern in practice: name what has complexity, inline what is trivial."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When named functions shine"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multi-step logic"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — validation, conditionals, multiple state updates, API calls. Multi-line inline arrows inside JSX become unreadable quickly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Shared by multiple elements"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if two or more elements call the same logic, define it once as a named function rather than duplicating an arrow."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Testability"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — named functions can be extracted, imported, and unit-tested in isolation from the component."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Self-documentation"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "onSubmit={handlePayment}"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " communicates intent at a glance; an inline arrow does not."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Side-by-Side: The Same Feature Both Ways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Here is the same \"add to cart\" button written both ways. The inline version works but buries intent. The named version is immediately readable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Inline — logic buried in JSX, hard to scan\nfunction ProductCard({ product, cartItems, setCartItems }) {\n  return (\n    <button\n      onClick={() => {\n        const existing = cartItems.find(i => i.id === product.id);\n        if (existing) {\n          setCartItems(cartItems.map(i =>\n            i.id === product.id ? { ...i, qty: i.qty + 1 } : i\n          ));\n        } else {\n          setCartItems([...cartItems, { ...product, qty: 1 }]);\n        }\n      }}\n    >\n      Add to Cart\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// ✅ Named — intent is clear; logic lives in one named place\nfunction ProductCard({ product, cartItems, setCartItems }) {\n  function handleAddToCart() {\n    const existing = cartItems.find(i => i.id === product.id);\n    if (existing) {\n      setCartItems(cartItems.map(i =>\n        i.id === product.id ? { ...i, qty: i.qty + 1 } : i\n      ));\n    } else {\n      setCartItems([...cartItems, { ...product, qty: 1 }]);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <button onClick={handleAddToCart}>Add to Cart</button>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The New-Function-Per-Render Question"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inline arrows create a new function object on every render. Named functions defined inside the component body do too — both are recreated each time the component renders. Neither avoids this by default."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n  // Both produce a new function reference on every render:\n  const inline = () => setCount(count + 1);\n  function named() { setCount(count + 1); }\n\n  // They are both new objects, so:\n  console.log(inline === inline); // false — compare across renders\n  console.log(named  === named);  // false — same\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For most components this does not matter. React's reconciler is fast and function allocation is cheap. The only time it matters is when you pass a handler to a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "React.memo"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " child or use it as a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useEffect"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " dependency — in those cases, wrap the function in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useCallback"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to stabilize the reference. That is an optimization step, not the default."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Reach for useCallback only after profiling confirms re-renders are a problem. Premature memoization adds complexity without measurable benefit in the vast majority of components."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using Both Together: the Most Common Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real components typically use both styles together. Named functions handle the primary actions; inline arrows handle simple props or argument passing."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function SearchBar({ onSearch }) {\n  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');\n  const [caseSensitive, setCaseSensitive] = useState(false);\n\n  // Named: multi-step logic deserves a name\n  function handleSearch(e) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    if (!query.trim()) return;\n    onSearch({ query: query.trim(), caseSensitive });\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSearch}>             {/* named */}\n      <input\n        value={query}\n        onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} {/* inline: one-liner */}\n        placeholder=\"Search…\"\n      />\n      <label>\n        <input\n          type=\"checkbox\"\n          checked={caseSensitive}\n          onChange={e => setCaseSensitive(e.target.checked)} {/* inline: one-liner */}\n        />\n        Case sensitive\n      </label>\n      <button type=\"submit\">Search</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extracting Handlers Outside the Component"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a handler does not use component state and only operates on its arguments, extract it as a pure function outside the component. This removes it from every render's function allocation, makes it trivially testable, and shareable across components."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Pure utility — no state, no closure — lives outside the component\nfunction formatPhoneNumber(value) {\n  const digits = value.replace(/\\D/g, '').slice(0, 10);\n  if (digits.length < 4) return digits;\n  if (digits.length < 7) return `(${digits.slice(0,3)}) ${digits.slice(3)}`;\n  return `(${digits.slice(0,3)}) ${digits.slice(3,6)}-${digits.slice(6)}`;\n}\n\nfunction PhoneInput() {\n  const [phone, setPhone] = useState('');\n\n  // Handler uses component state, so it stays inside\n  function handleChange(e) {\n    setPhone(formatPhoneNumber(e.target.value));\n  }\n\n  return <input value={phone} onChange={handleChange} placeholder=\"(555) 555-5555\" />;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Decision Guide"
          }
        ]
      },
