      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Readability in Lists: Avoid Multi-Line Inline Arrows"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The readability argument for named functions is strongest when inline arrows span multiple lines. JSX is already nested; a multi-line arrow inside a prop doubles the nesting and makes it hard to see where the JSX attributes end and the function body begins."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Multi-line inline — hard to read where JSX ends\n<button\n  onClick={() => {\n    if (!user) {\n      setError('Not logged in');\n      return;\n    }\n    setLiked(prev => !prev);\n    postLike(itemId, !liked);\n  }}\n>\n  Like\n</button>\n\n// ✅ Extracted to named handler — JSX is clean\nfunction handleLike() {\n  if (!user) {\n    setError('Not logged in');\n    return;\n  }\n  setLiked(prev => !prev);\n  postLike(itemId, !liked);\n}\n\n<button onClick={handleLike}>Like</button>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Inline vs Named Handlers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Named handlers can be tested by rendering the component and simulating the event — the same approach applies to inline arrows. But named handlers declared outside the component can also be unit-tested as pure functions without rendering anything."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// validate.js — pure function, no React\nexport function validateEmail(email) {\n  return email.includes('@') && email.includes('.');\n}\n\n// validate.test.js — no render needed\nimport { validateEmail } from './validate';\n\ntest('valid email passes', () => {\n  expect(validateEmail('alice@example.com')).toBe(true);\n});\n\ntest('missing @ fails', () => {\n  expect(validateEmail('notanemail')).toBe(false);\n});\n\n// In the component, use it inside the handler\nfunction handleSubmit(e) {\n  e.preventDefault();\n  if (!validateEmail(email)) {\n    setError('Invalid email');\n    return;\n  }\n  submitForm();\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extracting pure logic from handlers into standalone functions is the easiest path to testable event handling. The handler itself stays thin — mostly calling pure helpers — and the helpers are tested directly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Worked Example: Settings Panel"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This settings panel uses named handlers for complex operations and inline arrows for simple ones."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function SettingsPanel({ initialSettings, onSave }) {\n  const [settings, setSettings] = useState(initialSettings);\n  const [saved, setSaved]       = useState(false);\n\n  // Named: multi-step logic\n  function handleSave() {\n    if (!settings.username.trim()) return;\n    onSave(settings);\n    setSaved(true);\n    setTimeout(() => setSaved(false), 2000);\n  }\n\n  // Named: shared by multiple fields\n  function handleFieldChange(field, value) {\n    setSettings(prev => ({ ...prev, [field]: value }));\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <input\n        value={settings.username}\n        onChange={e => handleFieldChange('username', e.target.value)} {/* inline: passes arg */}\n        placeholder=\"Username\"\n      />\n      <input\n        value={settings.email}\n        onChange={e => handleFieldChange('email', e.target.value)}    {/* inline: passes arg */}\n        placeholder=\"Email\"\n      />\n      <label>\n        <input\n          type=\"checkbox\"\n          checked={settings.notifications}\n          onChange={e => handleFieldChange('notifications', e.target.checked)} {/* inline */}\n        />\n        Email notifications\n      </label>\n      <button onClick={handleSave}>                                          {/* named */}\n        {saved ? 'Saved!' : 'Save'}\n      </button>\n      <button onClick={() => setSettings(initialSettings)}>                   {/* inline: one-liner */}\n        Reset\n      </button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 1: Named function with parentheses"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Calls the function during render\n<button onClick={handleClick()}>Click</button>\n\n// ✅ Passes the reference\n<button onClick={handleClick}>Click</button>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 2: Multi-line arrow making JSX unreadable"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Logic buried in the JSX tree\n<form onSubmit={e => { e.preventDefault(); if (!email) { setError('required'); } else { login(email, pw); } }}>\n\n// ✅ Named handler — JSX describes structure; handler describes behavior\nfunction handleLogin(e) {\n  e.preventDefault();\n  if (!email) { setError('required'); return; }\n  login(email, pw);\n}\n<form onSubmit={handleLogin}>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 3: Duplicating inline arrows instead of extracting"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Same logic in two places — bug in one, not the other\n<button onClick={() => { setCount(0); setError(null); }}>Reset A</button>\n<button onClick={() => { setCount(0); setError(null); }}>Reset B</button>\n\n// ✅ Extract to a named function\nfunction handleReset() {\n  setCount(0);\n  setError(null);\n}\n<button onClick={handleReset}>Reset A</button>\n<button onClick={handleReset}>Reset B</button>"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Inline arrows are best for single-expression logic and closing over list-item variables."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Named functions are better for multi-step logic, shared handlers, and anything you want to test or document."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Both create new function objects each render — neither avoids this without useCallback."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Avoid multi-line inline arrows in JSX — extract them to named functions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pure logic (no state, no closure) can live outside the component for easy testing."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Real components mix both: named for primary actions, inline for simple prop wiring."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
